@node Odds format
@section Odds format

@vindex kelly-b-parameter-format
The user option @code{kelly-b-parameter-format} controls which odds format the @code{kelly} command prompts for (@ref{Calculating the optimal wager}).  The @emph{b} parameter in the Kelly formula represents the net odds received on a win; different betting traditions express the same information in different ways.

Five formats are supported:

@table @asis
@item @code{fractional-odds} (default)
Fractional (British) odds.  A value of @samp{3} means you receive 3 units of profit for every 1 unit wagered, plus your stake back.
@item @code{decimal-odds}
Decimal (European) odds.  A value of @samp{4.0} means a total return of 4 units per 1 unit wagered (equivalent to fractional odds of 3).  Must be greater than 1.
@item @code{moneyline-odds}
Moneyline (American) odds.  Positive values (e.g. @samp{+300}) indicate profit on a 100-unit stake; negative values (e.g. @samp{-150}) indicate how much you must stake to win 100 units.
@item @code{implied-probability}
The probability implied by the betting odds, expressed as a decimal between 0 and 1 exclusive (e.g. @samp{0.25}).
@item @code{implied-percent}
The same implied probability expressed as a percentage between 0 and 100 exclusive (e.g. @samp{25}).
@end table

The choice of format is purely a matter of convenience; all formats are converted internally to fractional odds before the Kelly calculation is performed.

@lisp
;; Use decimal (European) odds
(setq kelly-b-parameter-format 'decimal-odds)
@end lisp

@node Fractional Kelly
@section Fractional Kelly

@vindex kelly-fraction
The user option @code{kelly-fraction} is a multiplier applied to the computed Kelly fraction.  Its default value is @samp{1}, meaning the full Kelly recommendation is used.

In practice, the full Kelly criterion can lead to large swings in bankroll size, and many bettors prefer a more conservative approach.  Setting @code{kelly-fraction} to a value between 0 and 1 scales the recommended wager down proportionally.  For example, a value of @samp{0.5} (``half Kelly'') recommends wagering half of what the full Kelly formula suggests.

@lisp
;; Use half Kelly for a more conservative strategy
(setq kelly-fraction 0.5)
@end lisp

The value must be a positive number.  If it is zero, negative, or not a number, @code{kelly-calculate} signals an error (@ref{Core calculation}).

@node Bankroll
@section Bankroll

@vindex kelly-bankroll
The user option @code{kelly-bankroll} specifies the total amount of capital available for wagering.  The Kelly criterion expresses its recommendation as a fraction of the bankroll, so this value is needed to translate the fraction into a concrete monetary amount.

The default value is @code{nil}.  When @code{nil}, the @code{kelly} command prompts for a bankroll amount on the first invocation and stores the entered value in this variable for subsequent calls within the same session.  If you want to avoid the prompt, set it in your init file:

@lisp
(setq kelly-bankroll 10000)
@end lisp

@vindex kelly-bankroll-currency
The user option @code{kelly-bankroll-currency} specifies the currency symbol displayed alongside monetary amounts in the output.  The default value is @samp{"$"}.  Change it to match your local currency:

@lisp
(setq kelly-bankroll-currency "EUR")
@end lisp

