@node Calculating the optimal wager
@section Calculating the optimal wager

@findex kelly
The command @code{kelly} is the main entry point to the package.  Invoke it with @samp{M-x kelly RET} to calculate the optimal wager for a bet.

The command prompts for two inputs in sequence:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Win probability} --- your estimated probability that the bet will win, as a decimal between 0 and 1 exclusive.  For example, enter @samp{0.6} if you believe there is a 60% chance of winning.

@item
@strong{Betting odds} --- the odds offered on the bet, in whatever format @code{kelly-b-parameter-format} is set to (@ref{Odds format}).
@end enumerate

After collecting these inputs, the command computes the Kelly fraction using @code{kelly-calculate} (@ref{Core calculation}) and displays a message in the echo area with two pieces of information:

@itemize
@item
The @strong{amount to wager}, shown as both an absolute monetary value and a percentage of the bankroll.
@item
The @strong{expected net profit}, shown as both an absolute value and as a return-on-investment percentage.
@end itemize

If the Kelly fraction is zero or negative --- meaning the bet has non-positive expected value at the given odds --- the command instead displays a message advising against wagering.

Here is an example session using the default settings (fractional odds, full Kelly, $1000 bankroll):

@enumerate
@item
@samp{M-x kelly RET}
@item
@samp{Win probability: 0.6 RET}
@item
@samp{Fractional odds: 2 RET}
@end enumerate

The output might read:

@example
Amount to wager: $400.00 (40.00% of bankroll). Expected net profit: $160.00 (40.00% return on investment).
@end example

@node Functions
@chapter Functions

The following public functions are available for programmatic use.  They allow you to integrate Kelly criterion calculations into custom Elisp workflows without going through the interactive prompts.

@menu
